Simple little collapsible 3D viewer that fits inside an Altoids tin!
Very simple to print and build with an approximately one hour print time, depending on settings. Use 40% infill.
To view 3D images, just print off the image you want, downscaled to 8cm wide and 4.8cm tall and stick it to the base of the frame with sticky tac or something non-permanent.
Assembly is easy, just snap the pieces together! Watch the videos below for a demo (and to see the orientation of the parts): https://youtu.be/xozZniV_aIc
https://youtu.be/e-RquwnjZM4
When viewed through the lenses, you will see 3 images in a row, one to the left, one in the center, and one to the right. Just focus on the enter image and you'll see it in 3D! (There's no way to hide the left and right images without voiding the collapsibility.)
If you want to print out your own image, use this:
https://dj505gaming.wordpress.com/image_template_for_viewer/
It's already actual size, so paste your image overtop and print it out as-is. This project is free for use and modification by anyone, so long as you give credit and post a link to this project on any modifications.

Enjoy!

Word of warning: You might find it difficult to snap the arms together. Just bend the part between the hinges carefully. It's harder than you think to break, but still be careful when snapping the hinges together.

To assemble, print the pieces suitable for the convex lens you have (the shorter one for lenses with a smaller focal length, the taller ones for lenses with a larger focal length) and glue the lenses on to the faceplate, bulging side facing down. Then attach the flat arms to the base and attach the second set of arms, the ones with the hinge that's sticking out, to the flat ones. Make sure the part that's sticking out is pointing toward the outside, and the flat hinges are connected to the faceplate. To test whether it's together properly, try collapsing the legs inward and pushing the faceplate down into the tin.

title: PRUSA I3 - Cover of the connections of the power supply

description.text:
This Cover has been created in order to avoid small hands to touch the AC wires, and in addition to create the place for a Power Switch and a Volt-Amp meter.

Most Power Supplies are of the same size, so this Cover should fit in most cases, due to its versatility.

The Cover is fully open in the back and the bottom, so the air can still flow.

I created it to be used with my PRUSA I3.

The file originally made with SKETCHUP is also attached for eventual adaptations, especially for different accessories.

RELEASE NOTE FOR V3:
I did not print this last version yet, because I'm waiting for my new Volt-Am to arrive to remove the precedent one. However modifications from precedent version should not bring any troubles, because they are for small usage improvement and do not basically change anything.
(However, if you want to play safe, you still have the layouts of the precedent version)
I will update this text after having printed the V3. If you print it before me, please make it public, or let me know if you meet any problem. Thks.

V3 List of changes:

  • Structural reinforcements.
  • Aesthetic positioning of many 3mm holes on each sides, allowing the usage of any of them for a good fixation in each case (1 set of M3 bolt and nut on each side is perfect).
  • 2mm hole on the top of the 6.5 mm Power Switch hole, for the "position locker" of the switch.
  • Readjustment of the sizes of the holes on the facade, for a better immediate fitting with the accessories (25X45mm for the Volt-Amp, 8mm for the LED support, and 6.5mm for the Power Switch).
  • Edges have been smoothen.

V4 List of changes:

  • Thin (and easy to be removed in case of need to give way to the fingers to position the 2 nuts inside) bars have been added to the design into the bottom openings, in order to help to the printing of the edge of the rear-bottom structural reinforcement.
  • Note that due to the aforesaid modification, the cover can now be used in various positions of the Power Supply, and no more exclusively in the position which is shown on the photo.

comments.text: PLA will soften in direct sunlight and is too brittle for everyday usage. Example, leaving it in the back of the truck with full sunlight cause the PLA to soften and eventually fail. title: Nautilus Gears - One-sided bar with caps

description.text:
I was fascinated by these Nautilus Gears, and I decided to change the bar in order to avoid having anything covering the top of the gears, sort of "spoiling" the spiral effect you get when they turn fast.

I made a bar on the underneath of the gears, and just two caps clipping to the shafts to hold the gears in place.

I printed mine in black PLA, 0.2mm layer height on my Arduino Materia 101.

The "Nautilus_Gear.stl" file is the original one by MishaT.

Print (no support needed):

2x "Nautilus_gear.stl"
2x "Base_Cap.stl" (Print with hole facing upwards!)
1x "Base.stl"

Slide the gears on the shafts, paying attention to their initial position (which should be the one depicted in the photos I uploaded), then push the caps the whole way down on each shaft. They should fit snugly and keep the gears in position though allowing them to turn freely.

The lab needed to attach a portable webcam and a portable projector to pvc pipe, so I designed these models. I started with making the camera attachment with Autodesk Inventor (it needed to be printed almost solid because the camera insert portion was so thin). After a few trial and errors, I got the right size to slide in and out of the pvc. The flatten edge was made to make it easier for printing, and for insertion and removal. The tolerance is decent enough that the friction force works pretty well. Later, they asked me to make a similar attachment for a projector. So I recycled the pvc attachment, and a standard camera screw model to create a quick fix on in OpenSCAD.
Be careful, you do NOT want a plastic screw to break off inside your device. It can be difficult to get it back it. When in doubt, make the model thick and strong enough that it won't break.

title: QuorXZ: A String-driven, Core XZ 3D Printer

description.text:
A Core-XZ 3D printer inspired by Nicholas Seward's CoreXZ. The design of the QuorXZ uses OpenBuilds' OpenRail, V-Slot, and V-Wheels. When built with OpenBuilds' Build Plate and a standard 200 X 200 aluminum print bed, the print volume is 200 X 186 X 200. When built with the included custom print bed design, the print volume is 200 X 230 X 200.

10-10-15: The design is finished and the prototype has been built. It prints great!!

10-16-15: UPDATE! I've uploaded the complete set of files for the QuorXZ 3D printer. The zip file contains everything: printed parts, laser-cut parts, OpenSCAD source files, AND a fairly-complete Bill-of-Materials.

Update (9-5-2017): I have updated all files, and have created full assembly instructions over at OpenBuilds: http://openbuilds.com/builds/quorxz-a-string-driven-core-xz-printer.5489/ . There is also a complete and checked bill of materials with a "Buy sheet" with links to vendors for all of the parts. (The zip file that was posted here at thingiverse was out of date and has been deleted. The STL file posted here are still current.) If you are thinking of building one of these, check out the OpenBuilds resource.

See the extruder for the QuorXZ at http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:986423

There is CoreXZ firmware available for Marlin, Smoothie, and RepRap Duet. See http://forums.reprap.org/read.php?2,377858 for more details.
